{{wiktionary|sanctity|inviolability}}{{Abortion in the Catholic Church}}
In [[religion]] and [[ethics]], the '''inviolability''' or '''sanctity of life''' is a principle of implied protection regarding aspects of [[sentience|sentient]] life that are said to be holy, [[sacred]], or otherwise of such [[Value theory|value]] that they are not to be violated. This can be applied to both animals and humans, for instance in religions that practice [[Ahimsa]], as both are seen as holy and worthy of life.

The concept of inviolability is an important tie between the ethics of religion and the ethics of law, as each seeks justification for its principles as based on both purity and natural concept, as well as in universality of application.

==In Christianity==
{{Main article|Christianity and abortion}}
The phrase ''sanctity of life'' refers to the idea that human life is [[sacred]], [[holy]], and precious, argued mainly by the [[pro-life]] side in political and [[Morality|moral]] debates over such controversial issues as [[abortion]], [[contraception]], [[euthanasia]], [[embryonic stem-cell research]], and the "[[right to die]]" in the [[United States]], [[Canada]], [[United Kingdom]] and other [[English-speaking countries]]. (Comparable phrases are also used in other languages.) Although the phrase was used primarily in the 19th century in [[Protestant]] discourse, after [[World War II]] the phrase has been used in [[Catholic moral theology]] and, following ''[[Roe v. Wade]]'', [[Evangelicalism|Evangelical Christian]] moral rhetoric.<ref>{{cite book|author=Drutchas, Geoffrey Gilbert|title=Is Life Sacred? The Incoherence of the Sanctity of Life as a Moral Principle within the Christian Churches|publisher=Lancaster Theological Seminary|year=1996}}</ref>

The sanctity of life principle, which is often contrasted with the "[[Quality of Life (Healthcare)|quality of life]]" to some extent, is the basis of all [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] teaching about the fifth commandment in the [[Ten Commandments in Catholic theology|Ten Commandments]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rzIMeFZZuycC |title=Jewish and Catholic Bioethics: An Ecumenical Dialogue |editor1=[[Edmund Pellegrino|Edmund D. Pellegrino]] |editor2=Alan I. Faden |chapter=Jewish Teaching on the Sanctity and Quality of Life |author=Ronald M. Green |publisher=[[Georgetown University Press]] |year=1999 |isbn=9781589013506 |pages=25-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UyEEX73hytsC |title=Catholic Bioethics for a New Millennium |author=[[Anthony Fisher]] |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |year=2011 |isbn=9781139504881 |pages=238-239}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yyQll4Z1vjgC |title=Contemporary Catholic Health Care Ethics |author1=David F. Kelly |author2=Gerard Magill |author3=Henk ten Have |publisher=Georgetown University Press |year=2013 |isbn=9781589019614 |pages=32-38}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xNAfqSw9CxkC |title=The Fundamentals of Bioethics: Legal Perspectives and Ethical Aproches |author=Scaria Kanniyakonil |publisher=Oriental Institute of Religious Studies India |year=2007 |isbn=9788188456284 |pages=229-230}}</ref> 

== In Eastern religions ==
In Western thought, sanctity of life is usually applied solely to the human species ([[anthropocentrism]], sometimes called [[dominionism]]), in marked contrast to many schools of [[Eastern philosophy]], which often hold that all animal life is sacred―in some cases to such a degree that, for example, practitioners of [[Jainism]] carry brushes with which to sweep insects from their path, lest they inadvertently tread upon them.<ref>http://www.fas.harvard.edu/~pluralsm/affiliates/jainism/jainedu/5greatvows.htm</ref> [[George Carlin]], American social critic and author, challenged this viewpoint in his 1996 album and HBO special ''[[Back in Town (George Carlin album)|Back in Town]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://lybio.net/george-carlin-pro-life-abortion-and-the-sanctity-of-life/comedy/|title=George Carlin: Pro Life, Abortion, And The Sanctity Of Life|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|accessdate=}}</ref>

